This course is the continuation of MATH104 and MATH114, which are prerequisites. It covers Linear Algebra, Higher Order Differential Equations, Linear Differential Equations, and a review of vectors. The course uses Zill Cullen's Advanced Engineering Mathematics as its textbook and consists of exams and homework sets. &#8232;

Students tended to like the material that was covered, although most would have preferred a more practical approach over the theoretical, proofs-based approach used. Students furthermore felt that more material should be covered in lecture; one student complained that they “learned 90% of the material from the book and other students.”&#8232;

Students generally agreed that Professor Gluck was “brilliant” and passionate about lecturing, although they felt that his theoretical approach would have been “better suited to an even higher level math course.” Students claimed to attend Prof. Gluck's lectures regularly for his “enthusiasm and humor,” and his clarity when explaining concepts. Many students found him highly accessible outside of class during office hours. &#8232;

As a higher level mathematics course, this class consisted mainly of majors and minors in mathematics, engineering, and physics. Students found the material moderately difficult in that homework problems were much more difficult than those covered in lecture, and they required a certain amount of self-teaching. Exams were described as “too easy,” where most students performed well, making the curve extremely harsh. As such, students complained about exam grading, in which “a stupid computational error had detrimental effects on overall performance,” especially because there was a limited system of partial credit. Overall, students felt that the pacing and workload were fair, though perhaps insufficient for thorough learning.
